\pard\plain \tx0\tx360\tx720\tx1080\tx1440\tx1800\tx2160\tx2880\tx3600\tx4320\fi360\ltrch\loch {\f1\fs24\b0\i0 The Shalda continent is a big crescent slab of anthracite rock that tilts down into the strait of Hormuz like a sinking ship. The continent\loch\af1\hich\af1\dbch\af1\uc1\u8217\'92s gradual slope is not something that\u8217\'92s noticed by most of the people living there. You can\u8217\'92t see it with the naked eye. The land is just too big. All folk see is the local river tumbling downhill. And these are hardscrabble folk who move from task to task, people who, according to the mind of Danserd Fark, only know things of immediate utility. Danserd didn\u8217\'92t begrudge them their ignorance. He knew that it takes a person blessed with a life of leisure and wealth to travel to every corner of the continent, to map its major rivers, and then to wonder why they all flow in the same direction: North. }
\par\plain {\f1\fs24\b0\i0 The slope is most starkly seen if you start at sea level on a northern Shalda beach and then travel due south to one of the Hrkkan cliff cities that face the open ocean. Over the course of half a year you\loch\af1\hich\af1\dbch\af1\uc1\u8217\'92ll have ascended 1,000 leagues. Danserd had made the journey over twenty times. Only four of those times he was on official ambassadorial business. In times of late he no business other than sating his desire to discover new and fascinating kinds of plants. }
\par\plain {\f1\fs24\b0\i0 Plants, trees, grasses - the more Danserd looked the more he saw how the edges between these things was not so clear as it seemed. They were the key, he thought, to unlocking the truth behind so many mysteries, and first among these was question of Life itself; what is it?}
\par\plain {\f1\fs24\b0\i0 Are plants alive? Not everyone agrees. }
\par\plain {\f1\fs24\b0\i0 Danserd would ask this question to almost everyone he met, and generally speaking, people would say yes, plants are living creatures. They share so many of the attributes that intuitively define Life. }
\par\plain {\f1\fs24\b0\i0 Living things move. Plants move. They don\loch\af1\hich\af1\dbch\af1\uc1\u8217\'92t }{\f2\fs24\b0\i1 seem}{\f1\fs24\b0\i0  to move, but Danserd had taken the time to watch them}{\f1\fs24\b0\i0 . Thei}{\f1\fs24\b0\i0 r}{\f1\fs24\b0\i0  roots burrow inquiringly into the earth, the}{\f1\fs24\b0\i0 ir}{\f1\fs24\b0\i0  buds and twigs swing in definite }{\f1\fs24\b0\i0 arcs chasing the sun. In the space of one afternoon he\loch\af1\hich\af1\dbch\af1\uc1\u8217\'92d seen a vine-tendril }{\f1\fs24\b0\i0 circle }{\f1\fs24\b0\i0 around three times in a questioning arc, searching for something to latch on to.}
\par\plain {\f1\fs24\b0\i0 Living things grow. Plants grow. This point is obvious.}
\par\plain {\f1\fs24\b0\i0 Living things drink water. Plants drink water. This is a bit of the \loch\af1\hich\af1\dbch\af1\uc1\u8216\'91utility knowledge\u8217\'92 of hardscrabble folk. In all Danserd\u8217\'92s travels he found that no one was knew more about just how much water a certain plant needed, and moreover, what }{\f2\fs24\b0\i1 kind}{\f1\fs24\b0\i0  of water, as there are, for example, various weeds in the that thirst for a salty brine. These bulbous plants had different uses. Pickleweed. }
\par\plain {\f1\fs24\b0\i0 Living things have children. Plants have children. A seed is no different than egg. To reinforce this point, Danserd never used the word \loch\af1\hich\af1\dbch\af1\uc1\u8216\'91seed\u8217\'92. He\u8217\'92d say, \u8220\'93the oak\u8217\'92s eggs\u8221\'94 instead of \u8220\'93the oak\u8217\'92s acorns\u8221\'94, and he\u8217\'92d talk about the thing giving birth. But also because it annoyed his wife, Seculla.}
\par\plain {\f1\fs24\b0\i0 Living things eat. Do plants eat? Danserd believed that they did. In his magnificent garden he\loch\af1\hich\af1\dbch\af1\uc1\u8217\'92d planted some species of jackweed in pots that were filled with dark, loamy soil, the kind typical of the temperate valley of Hrk. Over the course of several months the potted soil started to brown. The jackweeds started to sag and its many stems started to limp. When Danserd re-potted the thing into fresh soil, it perked right back up again. Danserd knew this wasn\u8217\'92t proof, but it was a suggestion, nonetheless, that on the tips of the jackweed\u8217\'92s roots were little mouths that were sucking up not just water but food.}
\par\plain {\f1\fs24\b0\i0 Living things kill. This was a point raised by a shalzi slave that Danserd met in Agrahbah. To eat, one has to kill. This simple fact was woven into the man\loch\af1\hich\af1\dbch\af1\uc1\u8217\'92s cosmogony: the twinned creator gods were a capricious bunch. Story of God creating man as a cruel trick: His punishment: To eat you must kill a living thing. One cannot get sustenance from a rock. }
\par\plain {\f1\fs24\b0\i0 The slave\loch\af1\hich\af1\dbch\af1\uc1\u8217\'92s accord was thus; because plants are eaten, then they must be alive.}
\par\plain {\f1\fs24\b0\i0 Danserd then asked this slave the obvious question: if plants are alive, then they must be killing and eating as well, so what are plants killing? }
\par\plain {\f1\fs24\b0\i0 The slave said it was all a big circle, that the plants are killing and eating us. All living things are supposed to be immortal. But the plants are poisoning the air and then they feast on our corpses when we die. Birds, beasts, and beetles too. }
\par\plain {\f1\fs24\b0\i0 The man was a dog worshiper. He would feed his dead relatives to packs of dogs. The idea was to keep their corpses out of the ground and out of the reach of roots. He\loch\af1\hich\af1\dbch\af1\uc1\u8217\'92d grind whatever bones were leftover into dust and then he tossed that into the dog\u8217\'92s water trough. Then he made bricks out of the feces.}
\par\plain {\f1\fs24\b0\i0 Danserd had to consider it, because Humans do indeed kill to eat, as do all manner of beasts. It certainly seems that killing is a fact of life. }
\par\plain {\f1\fs24\b0\i0 There are certain Solean sects that say no. They say that life requires a measure of the spark, and plants lack awareness.}
\par\plain {\f1\fs24\b0\i0 Then there are Jandri folk how claim that plants are not alive because they do not breathe. Breath is the sign of life. }
\par\plain \f1\fs24\b0\i0
\par\plain {\f1\fs24\b0\i0 Breathing - fish breathe different substance, gives him the idea that plants breathe sunlight.}
\par\plain \f1\fs24\b0\i0
\par\plain {\f1\fs24\b0\i0 Danserd thought that plants were the most interesting thing about the journey up the Great Slope of Shalda. He\loch\af1\hich\af1\dbch\af1\uc1\u8217\'92d first have to travel south from always start deep south, to the Hrkkan highlands, were nothing grows taller than a footshrub because nothing can survive the winter if it grows above the snow drifts. Just north of that are the sparse woodlands of aspen and oak, and further north still is the belt of thick oak forest which stretches east and west across the whole continent. Further north still and the sun comes out and it gets hot enough in the summers to dry things out and spark fires, so the oaks forests cant compete with the fast growing grasses and fireproof palmettos. }
\par\plain {\f1\fs24\b0\i0 Then come the true lowlands, where swamp grasses and waterborne nuts }
